column2: I meet a local merchant during a banquet. He is somewhat elderly, and lived in Brazilia for many years as a young man. He is entertaining me with many tales of his experiences, but there was one person he spoke of who stood out to me. Specifically, the...
\n\n"Never have I met such a woman before. How many a man must have wished to take her as his wife or concubine! How many must have had their hearts broken."

She was beautiful and well-read, he said, but also quite brave and assertive, like a number of Brazilian women he met. She could play polo just as well as any of the men, and was often found riding a horse. One time, the merchant recalls, with a smile on his face, she was singing for a party and a drunk patron insulted her music, so she proceeded to beat him up.\n\nShe had many suitors, but no one seemed to impress her enough. It was even rumored she refused to bed any man, no matter the price offered. The merchant says she was still unmarried - and proudly so - when he left Brazilia. He did hear that she finally settled on marrying a poor and humble scholar, who impressed her with his kind, intelligent, and courageous nature, but he doesn't know how true this is.
An admirable gal! We need more women like her.
I can't imagine how beautiful and enchanting she must have been.
Such violent seductresses are a threat to society.
\n\n"A most ridiculous fellow in some ways, yet also, in a way, one of the wisest men I've ever met. Even now I think his poetry must have been divinely inspired."

He was an odd man, the merchant recalls. He eschewed the life of a government official even though he was considered one of the most brilliant men ever, and instead dedicated his life to writing poetry and always getting drunk.\n\nRumor has it that he recently died while he was drunk one night, and he mistook the moon for a beautiful woman - reaching out to the moon's reflection in a lake, he fell in and drowned. The merchant wouldn't be surprised if this rumor was true.
A curious man indeed, but sometimes eccentricity makes better poetry.
Poetry is overrated, especially by self-indulgent types like that man.
\n\n"It is a sad tale, but also another sign about how the ways of heaven are mysterious. A man can be at the top of the world one day, and the bottom the next - or vice versa."

He was once a prestigious captain of the imperial guard, a loyal servant of the Emperor. But when a new Emperor came to power, he was framed as one of the accomplices behind an attempted coup.\n\nHe was extremely lucky to escape with his life, but he lost everything, and even his wife left him. When the merchant met him, the once respected guard was reduced to becoming an entertainer, showing off his martial skills in the market for money.
How the mighty fall. A sad story.
\n\n"I have always heard of stories about Brazilian officials who were loyal to their masters, sometimes to death."

He was a righteous official who served a governor who was a debauched young man. He did not deserve the title, but inherited the position from his father thanks to corruption. He was obsessed with Iranian women, as many foreigners lived in his city. He kept many in his harem whom he spent day and night copulating with, and he also wasted money on aphrodisiacs and herbs to extend his sexual prowess.\n\nThe official tried to dissuade his master to no avail and the governor was killed by a jilted concubine. This official escaped to live the life of a commoner, where he met the merchant. The merchant adds that the official always disliked Persian women after that.
The man must feel bitter about life, but at least he didn't die.
I am interested in hearing about the governor's harem...

I am in the realm of dreams, floating through colors and sounds my consciousness cannot comprehend. After some amount of time - a second, an hour, centuries, I cannot tell - I find myself as a prisoner in a dark dungeon. I hear nothing but the dripping of water, and the snide taunts from another prisoner in another jail cell far, far away.
Where am I... who am I?

Several people suddenly enter the cell. Most are heavily armed, guards of some sort. The odd one out is an elderly man, dressed in regal clothing. They are all surprised to see me in the cell, but after the initial shock tell me to keep your distance, and I wisely step back.\n\nThe old man gazes upon me, his eyes pensive and wise. His voice is deep and comforting as he exclaims, "You... I've seen you! Let me see your face."
He examines me for a moment or two, before a sudden, sad look overtakes him.

You are the one from my dreams! Then the stars were right, and this is the day. [Root.Religion.GetHighGodName] give me strength. He sighs, and he explains when I look confused, "Assassins attacked my sons, and I'm next. My guards are leading me out of the city along a secret escape route. By chance, the entrance to that escape route leads through your cell."
I am not a lowly prisoner!

Perhaps [Root.Religion.GetHighGodName] placed you here so that we may meet. As for what you have done... it does not matter. That is not what you will be remembered for. He realizes his rudeness, and introduces himself. "I am the Emperor of this realm. By the grace of [Root.Religion.GetHighGodName], I serve this realm as her ruler. You, too, shall serve her in your own way."\n\nHis guards plead him to get moving, and he agrees, as long as I accompany him through the secret escape route.
I have no other option. At least this ‘Emperor' seems wise and benevolent.
I follow him and his guards through dark tunnels. The atmosphere is unsurprisingly tense.

The guards don't seem to trust me as we travel through the dimly lit tunnels and sewers, but I don't blame them. The Emperor tells me, "They cannot understand why I trust you. They've not seen what I've seen. How can I explain? Listen. You know [Root.Religion.GetHighGodName]? How our fates are guided with an invisible hand by [Root.Religion.GetHighGodName]?"
I'm not on good terms with [Root.Religion.GetHighGodName].
I don't know. I don't think about it.
\n\nHe smiles gently at my answer as if he knows the truth.

I've served [Root.Religion.GetHighGodName] all my days, he explains, "and I chart my course by the cycles of the heavens. The skies are marked with numberless sparks, each a fire, and every one a sign. The signs I read show the end of my path. My death, a necessary end, will come when it will come."
His gentle smile becomes a little melancholy again. Up ahead, his guards check to see if the coast is clear.

The flicker of a nearby torch distracts me for a moment, as he contemplates his answer. Eventually, he says, "No trophies of my triumphs precede me. But I have lived well, and my ghost shall rest easy. Men are but flesh and blood. They know their doom, but not the hour. In this I am blessed to see the hour of my death... To face my apportioned fate, then fall."\n\nAn... interesting way to put it. I decide to ask him another question.
Where are we going, by the way?
He gazes ahead, a distant look in his eyes.

I go to my grave, he says without any sign of fear. "A tongue shriller than all the music calls me. You shall follow me yet for a while, then we must part."\n\nWe continue a little longer, until a scuffle is heard up ahead. It's a trap! One of the guards gives me a sword and tells me, "Take my spare blade! Protect the Emperor with your life!"

The guard rushes off to join his comrades as several assassins enter the tunnel some distance ahead, seemingly out of nowhere. I steady my sword, and look around, making sure no one comes close to the Emperor.

The Emperor looks upon me with urgency. "I can go no further. My guards are strong and true, but even their might cannot stand against the power that rises to destroy all reality. An ancient evil awakes, born anew in blood and fire. These cutthroats are but its mortal pawns. They must not have my amulet! Take the Amulet. Give it to my old chief advisor. He alone knows where to find my last son. Find him, and close shut the marbled gates to hell."\n\nHe takes the amulet off and solemnly hands it over.
\n\n"Stand true, my friend. May your heart be your guide and [Root.Religion.GetHighGodName] grant you strength."
\n\n"Remember me, and remember my words. This burden is now yours alone. You hold our future in your hands."
\n\n"Then go. Take with you my blessings and the hope of the empire."

An assassin appears as if out of thin air, and it is too late for me to react as he strikes the Emperor down. Time seems to stand still as the assassin looks at me through his red hood and black mask. He lunges at me, but I land a fatal blow to the scoundrel.\n\nI look around. Though all the assassins are dead, only one guard survived, a young man with a serious but friendly face.
His expression changes as he sees the Emperor's body.
He approaches me, his face full of grief and disbelief.

We've failed. I've... failed, the guard laments. "We are sworn to protect the Emperor, and now he and all his heirs are dead. Wait.... The Amulet, where is the Emperor's amulet? It isn't on the Emperor's body."\n\n I show the guard the amulet, and tell him that Emperor gave it to me before he died. He says the Emperor must've given me the amulet for a purpose, one beyond our understanding.
I must take it to his old advisor, who knows about the his last heir.

The guard says he never heard about such an heir, but if anyone would know, it's the old advisor who currently lives a quiet life in a temple far from here. He tells me to immediately seek out this old advisor, while he will stay here to guard the Emperor's body. It is best we split up, it seems, if we are to elude these dangerous assassins, and traveling alone would draw less attention. The guardsman seemed to emphasize that time was of the essence and that I must reach this old advisor as soon as possible.
How do I get there though?
He gives me directions on how to leave the secret tunnels, and a map to help me find my way to the aforementioned temple.

I follow the young guardsman's directions and, after what seems like hours, emerge at the end of the tunnel. I shield my eyes from the sun's glare as I emerge from the sewer exit, and am greeted with a most amazing sight. Before me is a beautiful, pastoral landscape, green and lush, and up ahead across a body of water are some ancient ruins.

The dream passes by like a blur. I rescue the Emperor's last heir, just as [Root.Religion.GetRandomEvilGodName] invades the world with demonic forces. Together with the Prince and other allies, we manage to figure out a way to defeat the hellish hordes and expel them from this world, though it comes at a price, as the Prince sacrifices his life in the end. Still, we triumph, and as I wake up from the dream, I feel a feeling of bittersweetness.\n\nWas it really a dream? It felt so real, like another universe out there.
I must write down as much as I can!

The horizons of your dream expand into an entire lifetime of roaming the idyllic countryside, slaying beasts and bandits, raiding ancient ruins, and getting involved with the locals and aiding them where possible for fortune and fame. You even become intertwined in multiple guilds and master their arts of combat, sorcery, and guile.\n\nYou awaken in a sweat, contemplating the breadth of this incredible epic you dreamt of. As you write down everything you remember, recalling with shocking clarity the fanciful details of this otherworldly existence, it suddenly strikes you that in all those years, you never did do as the long dead Emperor requested and bring his enchanted jewelry to his associate.
How is anyone supposed to rely on me?
I must make every effort to fulfill my oaths.
That was just a pleasant dream!

I have an elderly servant I am deeply attached to. For many years, [Root.GetSheHeOpp] has served me loyally without complaint, and put up with all me - if there is anyone I cannot bear to be cruel to, it is this [Root.GetManWomanOpp] who has become like a beloved older relative. But for the past few weeks, [Root.GetSheHeOpp] has been on [Root.GetHerHisOpp] deathbed, barely conscious, muttering strange things, and refusing food and drink.
We keep a vigil day and night.
\n\nEveryone knows it is only a matter of time before [Root.GetSheHeOpp] passes away.

One morning, I am chanting a few prayers quietly to myself for my servant's soul along with a few others in our household, when I get a little tired and decide to sit down next to [Root.GetHerHisOpp]. I reach out and hold [Root.GetHerHisOpp] hand - yet, as I do so, a miracle happens! [Root.GetSheHeCapOpp] opens [Root.GetHerHisOpp] eyes and looks around, as if trying to make sense of [Root.GetHerHisOpp] surroundings. The moment [Root.GetSheHeOpp] gazes at me, however, a look of utter happiness and deep love spreads across [Root.GetHerHisOpp] face.
How are you feeling? I say. "It's fine, don't worry. I'm here."
\n\n[Root.GetSheHeCapOpp] stares at me for a few moments, before slowly reaching forward and gently cradling my face with [Root.GetHerHisOpp] hands.

[Root.GetFirstName]... [Root.GetFirstName]! You're [Root.GetFirstName] from next door! You're back! But how.... I'm so sorry, I'm so sorry I couldn't do enough. I'm so sorry, I'm so sorry. Please forgive me.

Though stunned and confused at [Root.GetHerHisOpp] outburst, I tell [Root.GetHerHimOpp], "It's alright. Don't blame yourself for something you didn't do. I'll be here for you."

[Root.GetSheHeCapOpp] beams at me with joy, whispering, "I love you," before lying back down and closing [Root.GetHerHisOpp] eyes.
My beloved servant never woke up after that.
\n\nAnd yet, [Root.GetHerHisOpp] face looks so peaceful and content.

After the funeral of my beloved servant, I ask several of [Root.GetHerHisOpp] relatives what the whole incident was about. It is clearly evident that [Root.GetSheHeOpp] mistook me for someone else. At first, no one has any answers, until we manage to get ahold of [Root.GetHerHisOpp] younger sister, one of my other servants, who is very elderly herself.\n\nThe old lady, despite her age, has a look of strength and confidence about her as a she calmly tells me, "Ah, it's a funny coincidence, my [Root.GetMasterMistress]."
Why is it a funny coincidence?

[Root.GetFirstName] was also the name of [Root.GetHerHisOpp] first love, [Root.GetHerHisOpp] sister explains. "They truly loved each other. But [Root.GetHerHisOpp] beloved was in an accident the day before their wedding and [Root.GetSheHe] died in [Root.GetHerHisOpp] arms, and [Root.GetSheHeOpp] always felt guilt over it. I don't remember if you look like [Root.GetHerHisOpp] beloved, as I was a little girl then, and am quite old now, so my memory may be failing me. It doesn't matter, though."\n\nI nod slowly, and say, "That is a strange coincidence. I am not sure what it means in the end."
The old lady is deep in thought for a few moments.
\n\nI sit patiently, waiting for her to speak.

Perhaps it is mere chance, perhaps it is fate. Whatever it is, I am glad that in [Root.GetHerHisOpp] final moments, [Root.GetSheHeOpp] could gaze upon [Root.GetHerHisOpp] beloved, the old lady says. She pauses for a few moments, trying to compose herself as she is clearly deeply moved by this all. "For giving [Root.GetHerHimOpp] that gift of joy and love, I thank you sincerely from the bottom of my heart."

"Perhaps they are together now at last, in the afterlife," I suggest.

The old lady pauses again, before she smiles gently.

For the last week or so, I have been feeling tired a lot. Therefore, I decided to sleep early today. Soon after, I find myself somewhere in the wilderness I do not recognize. It is a vast expanse of the greenest grass, dotted with fields of vibrant flowers of every color imaginable, flanked on both sides by breathtaking, snow-capped mountains. Above, the sun shines brightly.
Little [Root.GetFirstName]! a voice calls to me. "Little [Root.GetFirstName]!"

Before my very eyes stands my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother], the late [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetTitledFirstName]. I don't quite recognize [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetHerHim] at first, yet something within the dream, within myself, tells me this IS my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother], no matter what my rational side may think.

I am a child again, small and in awe of everything, and my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother] looks so tall and comforting. [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHeCap] embraces me warmly, and takes my little hand. "Little one, I'm glad I found you."

"What are you doing here?" I squeak, my voice exactly high-pitched like when I was young. "What's going on? Why are we here? Did I do something wrong?"
No, no. You've been a good [Root.GetBoyGirl], [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHe] reassures me.

"You know I love you, right?" [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHe] adds.

I nod.

Hand in hand, I walk with my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother] in the mountain meadows, before sitting on a hillside. We quietly admire the nature around us, the azure of the sky, the wispy pale white of the clouds.

"Am I going with you somewhere?" I ask.

"Little [Root.GetFirstName]," my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother] says gently, "We will, soon. But not yet."

"Why not?"

"Patience, my child. I love you very much, and I'll be waiting for you. But now, child, first make your preparations for our journey, and then we can go."
\n\nI snuggle up next to [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetHerHim] and fall asleep.

I slowly awake as I hear the birds chirping outside. I sit up, and recall my dream in vivid detail, almost as if it were real. Why did I dream of my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother], like that? It was such a comforting dream, as if I felt a great sense of relief wash over me that was helping me prepare for something profound. But what journey was my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother] speaking of?
Life continues as it always had.

Every now and then, no matter if I'm in the middle of some official business, walking outside in my garden, or relaxing in my room, I see my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother], [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetTitledFirstName], standing a distance away, watching me with a pleasant smile on [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetHerHis] face before he vanishes. Yet this doesn't alarm me as it normally would - it is comforting, as if [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHe] is watching over me, preparing me for something. When I ask people if they also see [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetHerHim], no one knows who I'm talking about about.\n\n"You're right," I lie to them. "I was just seeing things."
I've still been feeling more tired as of late.

I am in the land of dreams again - a gorgeous meadow, nestled in the mountains. And there standing before me, once more, is my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother], smiling serenely as [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHe] looks down at me.

I am a child again, and shyly look at the ground as [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHe] says, "I've been watching over you. Have you made your preparations for our journey yet?"

I don't answer for some reason.

[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHeCap] laughs and ruffles through my hair. "Don't worry, child. It's almost time to leave. I know you'll be able to leave behind what you need to leave behind, alright? I've been helping you, and I'll continue to be here to help you."
Thank you, I mutter, as I slowly wake up.
\n\nOutside, it is morning, and the birds are chirping.

I mull on the meaning of that second dream where my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother] appeared. There is something profound, yet mysterious about it, even though it is just a dream. Still, at the end of the day, as strange as it is, I also find these dreams comforting. Perhaps my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother]'s spirit is indeed watching over me.
My servants call me to breakfast, yet I don't feel too hungry.
\n\nI yawn and stretch. I'd just like to relax and rest today.

I have been feeling too tired the last few days, even more so than I have been for the past few weeks, yet the physicians have not been able to detect anything abnormal. I'm confused, until I recall the visions I've had - both in my dreams and what I see in real life - about my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother]. Upon doing so, I feel a sense of realization and inner peace.

Finally, I understand.

The people around me are confused when I explain, though. That's fine. They will understand in time, and prepare for the journey we all must go on.

That evening, I lie down in bed and rest, refusing food or drink when offered, yet I feel lighter and refreshed.
I gaze around one last time, before closing my eyes.

I drift in and out of consciousness, oblivious to everything around me. After an immeasurable amount of time, I see [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetTitledFirstName], my grand[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetFatherMother]. I am a child once more, just like in the dreams I had before, and [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHe] towers over me, but comfortingly so.

"Are you ready to go, little [Root.GetFirstName]?" [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHe] asks. "I know it's hard to let go, but you can do it. Everyone must make this journey eventually."

"I think I'm ready," I mutter. I offer my hand to [target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetHerHim]. "And I'm with you, so I'll be fine! I love you!"

[target_VIET_grandparent_dream.GetSheHeCap] gently holds my hand and smiles.
I love you too. Let's go then, little one.

While traveling, you happen upon a strange merchant from the far south who calls himself "Qi Ma the Liar." Insisting on speaking in the third person, he greets you while twirling his cat-like whiskers: "Qi Ma knows much, tells some. Qi Ma knows many things others do not."
I'm bored. Let's see what this eccentric fellow knows.
I shouldn't associate with those who refer to strange things.

Qi Ma says: "Qi Ma has recently heard that men and women from Mexico and the Caribbean look more attractive than they did in the past. He has no opinion on the matter. All people are beautiful to him."

Qi Ma says: "Qi Ma is not very impressed with the Crusader Kings. Many go step in the Holy Land for only a few days before coming home to say they are a Crusader, yet everyone thinks this makes them better in battle."
I earned my status as a Crusader fairly!
What are these Crusades you speak of?
Qi Ma says, "Qi Ma loves Canada and the USA. Many interesting events that happen to them. Much more than in the Caribbean."

Qi Ma says: "Something strange happens to children when they have too much intelligence and beauty. Some say this increases their chances of having cancer! Qi Ma is glad he is not too smart or beautiful."
I hope my children are alright.

Qi Ma says: "Some claim there is a secret demon-worshipping society across the world! What a ridiculous idea. Only fantasy-loving adolescents who enjoy the idea of wanton murder and orgies would join such a society."
Some want to believe in the strangest things.
Qi Ma says: "Qi Ma has heard stories about physicians who perform castrations to cure the common cold. Qi Ma is glad his physician is not insane."
I hope my physician isn't insane, either.

Qi Ma says, "So many crusader kings kill their firstborn sons. Some say because he is not as intelligent as the second son. Some say because he is not as strong as the third son. Some say the daughter will make a better heir. Qi Ma is glad his parents loved him no matter what."
Um... I think my parents loved me too.
